My First R Notebook

This is an R Notebook that shows you how to create an R Notebook!

I love R Notebooks because they can be used to generate word documents or html files from your code. So you can create your code and send it to anyoneeven people that dont have R.

First, open up RStudio. It should look something like this:

Your background might be white. If youd like to change it, go to RStudio>Preferences>Appearance. (If youre on a mac. If youre on a PC, google is your friend!)

The console takes up most of the space on the left side of the screen. The console is a place where you can enter R commands one line at a time. If youd like, you run your analyses this way: one way line at a time.

Instead of the console, you could create a script file. The script file would then take up most of the space on the left side of the screen. A script file is kinda like an SPSS syntax file. Its a list of commands for R. If youd like, you could run your analyses that waytype your commands into the script file and then run them. Whats good about script files is the same as whats good about SPSS syntax filesyou have a record of the analyses you did.

To create a new R Notebook file, go to File > New File > R Notebook

Now RStudio should look something like this for you:

Now the R Notebook takes up most the space on the left side of the screen.

Take a look at the right side of the screen. There are two windows there. The top window tells you information about R environment.

The bottom window has a number of tabs. This is a useful place to quickly access your file directory, the packages that can be loaded, and also output. I like to see my output side by side with my code, so lets enlarge the bottom window so it takes up the entire right side of the screen. Either you can drag it up or press the maximize button in the corner.

Now youre RStudio should look something like this.

I want to show you something cool about R Notebooks. You can press the Preview button anytime and a preview of your output document will appear in the Viewer on the right side of the screen. The preview button can be found on the left side of the screen above your R Notebook.

Try pressing it now. First you will be asked to save your Notebook. If you press it again, after saving, your screen should look something like this:

Voila! If you look in the folder where you saved your R Notebook, youll see an html file that can be opened in any web browser and looks just like the preview on the left side of your screen.

Another great thing about the Preview button is everytime you press it, not only do you get a preview of your output document, it also automatically saves your file.

Ok, lets turn back to the right side of the screen. Youll notice there seem to be different sections of text. Lets talk about what each section does.

First, the header.

This basic header contains two pieces of information. The title of the notebook and the type of output file. You can change both just by typing.

Try it out now. Change the title to My First R Notebook and then press preview. You should see the title of your output doc has changed now.

You can change the output type the same way. Just type the output style youd like! Here is a list of possible output types. Feel free to try them out. Each one shoud produce a new document of that type in the same folder you saved your R Notebook file.

  • html_document
    • regular html page, not an R Notebook html page. An R Notebook html page is a self-contained document that includes all output.
  • pdf_document
    • a pdf
  • word_document
    • a word documentthis is useful for writing manuscripts. Imagine your analysis is automatically exported to word! If you make a small change, no problemits already in the manuscript!
  • odt_document
    • Open Document Text file
  • rtf_document
    • Rich Text format
  • md_document
    • markdown document
  • github_document
    • Github compatible markdown document
  • ioslides_presentation
    • ioslides html presentation
  • slidy_presentation
    • slidy html slides presentation
  • beamer_presentation
    • beamer pdf slides

However, I recommend sticking with html_notebook.

Now lets take a look at the code below the header.

Markdown example

Youll notice its mostly plain text with a few weird brackets and asterisks.

This plain text is written according to the rules of Markdown. You can download a cheatsheet with all the rules of Markdown here

Importantly, you can italicize text by surrounding it with asterisks like this: italics

You can bold text by surrounding it with double asterisks like this: bold

One thing to keep in mind: When you want to start a new line, add two spaces to the end of the previous line. You cant just press enter and start a line.

Try writing some text yourself and then pressing the preview button to see what it looks like.

Ok, lets look at the next section of code:

This is a code chunk. It starts with three ticks (above the tab key. NOT an apostrophe). It ends with three ticks. Inside the curly brackets is the letter r. That tells RStudio that this is a chunk of R code. That might seem obvious but you can actually put in lots of different code chunks here. You can also add Bash, Python, Rcpp, SQL, and Stan code chunks.

To add a code chunk. Press the insert button in the menubar and then select R.

Lets write and execute your first R code!

Type the following into a new R chunk.

First we assign the value Hellow World! This is my first R variable to the variable myFirstVariable. Then we told RStudio to print the value of that variable.
Press Preview and see your code in action. And thats the basics of R Notebooks! You can do a lot just with Markdown without even writing any code in R!
